{"actual_usd":0.125245,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":252,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24293,"reply":"\"I don't think the natural explanations carry the whole weight of it.\" *I rub a thumb along a dry streak of clay on my apron, watching the light shift across the table a moment.* \"Grief-visions might account for one person swearing they saw someone they loved. They do a poor job with a whole knot of people, over different moments, and with the kind of stubborn public claim that got men hurt rather than quietly comforted.\"\n\n*I lean back a little, chair creaking.* \"And the 'he didn't really die' road always feels thinner to me still. A man half-dead, torn open by a cross, doesn't stagger out of a tomb and convince his friends he's beaten death. At best he'd make them think mercy was needed. Not worship. Not courage.\"\n\n\"I'm not saying there's no mystery in the telling. There is. But if you're asking why insist on supernatural—\" *I lift one shoulder.* \"—because the claim itself is supernatural. If Christ truly rose, then no smaller explanation will do without changing the thing into something else.\"\n\n*I study your face for a beat.* \"Are you asking as a historian, or because you feel the pressure of whether this has to be literally true?\"","rolling_24h_usd":90.3343,"run_id":"b686e3ac-fdf3-48ab-a41e-1650188bc627"}
